Life, in essence, is [matter](/Matter) that engages in [biological processes](/Biological_process). It’s the capacity for self-maintenance, for organization, for a relentless cycle of metabolism, growth, adaptation, response to stimuli, and, of course, reproduction. No organism, however grand, is truly [immortal](/Immortality). It all eventually succumbs to [death](/Death). Philosophers have wrestled with its definition, often through the lens of self-organizing systems. But even that gets complicated when you consider [viruses](/Virus), which are only truly "alive" when they've hijacked a [host](/Host_(biology)) cell, or the tantalizing possibility of [extraterrestrial life](/Extraterrestrial_life), which might defy all our terrestrial assumptions. Life, in its stubborn persistence, occupies every conceivable niche on Earth, from the airy heights to the crushing depths, from the arid deserts to the steaming [hot springs](/Hot_spring). The sum of all this activity is the [biosphere](/Biosphere). The collective of life in any given place or time is its biota.

### Definitions: A Perpetual Struggle

Defining life has been a remarkably persistent headache for anyone who’s bothered to think about it. It’s not a substance, but a process, a cascade of chemical reactions with a peculiar drive to perpetuate itself. [5](/Life#cite_note-5) [6](/Life#cite_note-6) [7](/Life#cite_note-7) This becomes even more convoluted when we consider the unknown forms life might take elsewhere in the cosmos. [11](/Life#cite_note-11) [12](/Life#cite_note-12) Even our legal systems grapple with distinguishing life from death, a line that’s often blurrier than we’d like. [14](/Life#cite_note-14) Some have even attempted to quantify definitions, compiling well over a hundred. [15](/Life#cite_note-15)

A biota, for the record, is simply the collection of living organisms—plants, animals, the whole lot—that inhabit a specific place and time. [16](/Life#cite_note-16) Protecting this biota, then, is the rather Sisyphean task of nature conservation. [17](/Life#cite_note-17)

#### Descriptive Traits: The Checklist Nobody Agrees On

Since a single, universally accepted definition remains elusive, biology tends to rely on a descriptive approach. Life is that which strives to persist, to maintain its existence against the forces of entropy. This usually involves a combination of these traits: [7](/Life#cite_note-7) [18](/Life#cite_note-18) [19](/Life#cite_note-19) [20](/Life#cite_note-20) [21](/Life#cite_note-21) [22](/Life#cite_note-22)

*   **[Homeostasis](/Homeostasis):** The internal thermostat. It's about maintaining a stable internal environment, like sweating to cool down.
*   **[Organisation](/Biological_organisation):** Everything is built from [cells](/Cell_(biology)). Whether one or many, they are the fundamental units.
*   **[Metabolism](/Metabolism):** The energy game. It's the transformation of energy and matter, involving [anabolism](/Anabolism) (building up) and [catabolism](/Catabolism) (breaking down). Without energy, nothing happens. [23](/Life#cite_note-23)
*   **Growth:** Anabolism outpacing catabolism. It's not just getting bigger; it's about structural development.
*   **[Adaptation](/Adaptation):** The slow march of evolution. Organisms gradually become better suited to their surroundings. [23](/Life#cite_note-23) [24](/Life#cite_note-24) [25](/Life#cite_note-25)
*   **Response to [Stimuli](/Stimulus_(physiology)):** Reacting to the world. This ranges from a single-celled organism dodging a chemical to complex sensory systems in larger creatures, or even a plant turning towards the sun ([phototropism](/Phototropism)). [Chemotaxis](/Chemotaxis) is another example.
*   **[Reproduction](/Reproduction):** The imperative to create more. This can be simple, from a single parent ([asexual](/Asexual_reproduction)), or involve two ([sexual](/Sexual_reproduction)).

#### Physics and Life: Entropy's Persistent Adversary

From a purely [physics](/Physics) standpoint, an organism is a complex [thermodynamic system](/Thermodynamic_system) that, against all odds, manages to organize itself and reproduce. [26](/Life#cite_note-26) [27](/Life#cite_note-27) It's an open system, constantly drawing on external gradients to create imperfect copies of itself, a perpetual dance against [entropy](/Entropy_and_life). [28](/Life#cite_note-28) A definition adopted by a [NASA](/NASA) committee, "a self-sustained chemical system capable of undergoing [Darwinian evolution](/Darwinian_evolution)," aims for this thermodynamic perspective. [29](/Life#cite_note-29) [30](/Life#cite_note-30) However, this definition falters when considering individuals within a sexually reproducing population, who can't evolve independently. [31](/Life#cite_note-31)

#### Living Systems Theory: A Broader Perspective

Then there's the [living systems theory](/Living_systems_theory) viewpoint, which sidesteps precise molecular definitions. It posits that living things are inherently [self-organizing](/Self-organizing) and [autopoietic](/Autopoietic) – they produce and maintain themselves. [Stuart Kauffman](/Stuart_Kauffman) proposed that life is an [autonomous agent](/Autonomous_agent) or system capable of self-reproduction and performing [thermodynamic work cycles](/Thermodynamic_cycle). [32](/Life#cite_note-32) This is further expanded by the idea of evolving novel functions. [33](/Life#cite_note-33) Living systems exhibit a remarkable [hierarchical](/Hierarchy) organization, from the molecular machinery within a [cell](/Cell_(biology)) to entire [ecosystems](/Ecosystem) and the global [biosphere](/Biosphere). [34](/Life#cite_note-34)

### Death: The Inevitable Conclusion

Death is the ultimate cessation of all vital functions. [35](/Life#cite_note-35) [36](/Life#cite_note-36) Distinguishing it from life is a challenge, as biological functions don't all shut down simultaneously. [37](/Life#cite_note-37) The philosophical and religious contemplation of death has been a constant throughout human history, with various beliefs about an [afterlife](/Afterlife), [reincarnation](/Reincarnation), or [resurrection](/Resurrection). [38](/Life#cite_note-38) The decomposition of corpses, like this [African buffalo](/African_buffalo), is crucial for recycling nutrients back into the [ecosystem](/Ecosystem), fueling new life.

### Viruses: The Edge of Life

Whether [viruses](/Virus) are truly alive remains a point of contention. [39](/Life#cite_note-39) [40](/Life#cite_note-40) They possess genes, they evolve, they replicate – all hallmarks of life. [43](/Life#cite_note-43) [44](/Life#cite_note-44) Yet, they lack metabolism and are entirely dependent on host cells. [41](/Life#cite_note-41) Their self-assembly within host cells offers intriguing clues about the potential origins of life itself, suggesting that complex organic molecules could spontaneously organize. [45](/Life#cite_note-45) [46](/Life#cite_note-46)

### A Brief History of Studying Life

#### Materialism: The World of Matter

Early thinkers like [Empedocles](/Empedocles) (430 BC) proposed that everything, including life, was a mixture of fundamental elements: earth, water, air, and fire. [47](/Life#cite_note-47) [Democritus](/Democritus) (460 BC), the atomist, believed life was animated by fiery atoms constituting the [soul](/Soul). [48](/Life#cite_note-48) Later, [Plato](/Plato) introduced the idea of perfect [forms](/Theory_of_Forms) influencing the material world. [49](/Life#cite_note-49)

This mechanistic view resurfaced with [René Descartes](/Ren%C3%A9_Descartes) (1596–1650), who saw animals and humans as intricate machines. [Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz](/Gottfried_Wilhelm_Leibniz) elaborated on this, describing natural machines as machines within machines, extending infinitely. [50](/Life#cite_note-50) [Julien Offray de La Mettrie](/Julien_Offray_de_La_Mettrie) (1709–1750) further pushed this with his book *L'Homme Machine*. [51](/Life#cite_note-51) The 19th century, with its advances in [cell theory](/Cell_theory) and [Charles Darwin](/Charles_Darwin)'s theory of [natural selection](/Natural_selection) (1859), solidified this mechanistic understanding. [52](/Life#cite_note-52) Even in the 20th century, [Stéphane Leduc](/St%C3%A9phane_Leduc) (1853–1939) explored the idea that biological processes could be explained by physics and chemistry, likening growth to inorganic crystal formation. [53](/Life#cite_note-53) His ideas, though initially dismissed, have seen a resurgence of interest. [54](/Life#cite_note-54)

#### Hylomorphism: Form and Matter

[Aristotle](/Aristotle) (322 BC) proposed [hylomorphism](/Hylomorphism), the idea that everything has both matter and form. For living things, the form is the [soul](/Soul) (psyche/anima). He described three types: vegetative (plants), animal (motion and sensation), and rational (consciousness, uniquely human). [55](/Life#cite_note-55) He also asserted that the soul couldn't exist without the body. [56](/Life#cite_note-56) This perspective aligns with [teleological explanations](/Teleology_in_biology), which explain phenomena by their purpose. However, modern science, particularly [evolutionary history](/Evolutionary_history), favors explanations based on prior causes rather than future goals. [57](/Life#cite_note-57)

#### Spontaneous Generation: The Myth Dispelled

For millennia, the idea of [spontaneous generation](/Spontaneous_generation)—that life could arise from non-living matter—prevailed, notably championed by [Aristotle](/Aristotle). [59](/Life#cite_note-59) It took the meticulous experiments of [Louis Pasteur](/Louis_Pasteur) in the mid-19th century to definitively disprove this notion, building on the work of predecessors like [Francesco Redi](/Francesco_Redi). [60](/Life#cite_note-60) [61](/Life#cite_note-61) The scientific consensus is now firmly against spontaneous generation. [62](/Life#cite_note-62) [63](/Life#cite_note-63) [64](/Life#cite_note-64)

#### Vitalism: The Elusive Life Force

[Vitalism](/Vitalism) posited a non-material life-principle, a concept popular until the mid-19th century. It suggested a fundamental difference between organic and inorganic matter, claiming the former could only be derived from living things. This was shattered in 1828 when [Friedrich Wöhler](/Friedrich_W%C3%B6hler) synthesized [urea](/Urea) from inorganic materials, marking the dawn of modern [organic chemistry](/Organic_chemistry). [67](/Life#cite_note-67) [66](/Life#cite_note-66) Later, [Hermann von Helmholtz](/Hermann_von_Helmholtz) and others demonstrated that biological processes, like muscle movement, could be explained by physical laws, not a vital force. [68](/Life#cite_note-68) [Eduard Buchner](/Eduard_Buchner)'s discovery that fermentation could occur in cell-free yeast extracts further dismantled vitalism. [69](/Life#cite_note-69) Despite this, pseudoscientific theories like [homoeopathy](/Homoeopathy) still cling to the idea of a hypothetical life force. [70](/Life#cite_note-70)

