The story of life is a long one, stretching back billions of years.

*   **[Earth formed](/Age_of_Earth)** (approx. 4.54 billion years ago)
*   **[Earliest water](/Origin_of_water_on_Earth)** appeared early in Earth's history.
*   **[LUCA](/Last_universal_common_ancestor)**, the presumed ancestor of all current life, emerged.
*   **[Earliest fossils](/Earliest_known_life_forms)** provide tangible evidence of early life.
*   The atmosphere began to change with the advent of **[Photosynthesis](/Evolution_of_photosynthesis)**.
*   **[Single-celled life](/Unicellular_organism)** dominated for eons.
*   The **[Great Oxidation Event](/Great_Oxidation_Event)** drastically altered the planet's chemistry.
*   **[Sexual reproduction](/Evolution_of_sexual_reproduction)** revolutionized genetic diversity.
*   **[Multicellular life](/Multicellular_organism)** arose, leading to greater complexity.
*   The **[Neoproterozoic oxygenation event](/Neoproterozoic_oxygenation_event)** further shaped life.
*   The **[Ediacaran biota](/Ediacaran_biota)** represents the first complex multicellular organisms.
*   The **[Cambrian explosion](/Cambrian_explosion)** saw a rapid diversification of animal life.
*   **[Plants](/Evolutionary_history_of_plants)** colonized land.
*   **[Arthropods](/Arthropod)** and **[Molluscs](/Evolution_of_molluscs)** diversified.
*   The first **[Tetrapods](/Tetrapod)** ventured onto land.
*   **[Dinosaurs](/Dinosaur)** ruled for an era.
*   **[Mammals](/Evolution_of_mammals)** and **[Birds](/Evolution_of_birds)** emerged.
*   **[Flowers](/Fossil_history_of_flowering_plants)** appeared.
*   **[Primates](/Evolution_of_primates)** evolved, eventually leading to... us.

### Origin of Life: A Spark in the Primordial Soup

The Earth is approximately 4.54 [billion years](/Bya) old. [71](/Life#cite_note-71) Life, however, has been around for at least 3.5 billion years, [72](/Life#cite_note-72) [73](/Life#cite_note-73) [74](/Life#cite_note-74) [75](/Life#cite_note-75) with the oldest physical evidence—[biogenic](/Biogenic) [graphite](/Graphite)—dating back to 3.7 billion years ago. [76](/Life#cite_note-76) Molecular clock estimates suggest life might have originated even earlier, around 4.0 billion years ago. [78](/Life#cite_note-78) Theories on this origin attempt to explain the leap from simple [organic molecules](/Organic_molecule) to the first [protocells](/Protocell) and the emergence of metabolism. [79](/Life#cite_note-79) In 2016, scientists tentatively identified 355 genes belonging to the [last universal common ancestor](/Last_universal_common_ancestor). [80](/Life#cite_note-80)

The [biosphere](/Biosphere) is thought to have begun its development around 3.5 billion years ago. [81](/Life#cite_note-81) Beyond the graphite evidence, [microbial mat](/Microbial_mat) [fossils](/Fossils) from 3.48 billion-year-old [sandstone](/Sandstone) in [Western Australia](/Western_Australia) provide further testament. [77](/Life#cite_note-77) Even older, though still debated, are the "remains of [biotic life](/Biotic_life)" found in 4.1 billion-year-old rocks in Western Australia. [72](/Life#cite_note-72) More recently, putative fossilized [microorganisms](/Microorganism) were reported from [hydrothermal vent precipitates](/Hydrothermal_vent) in Quebec, Canada, dating back a staggering 4.28 billion years. [82](/Life#cite_note-82) This suggests life may have sprung forth almost immediately after the oceans formed, a mere blink of an eye after the Earth itself coalesced.

### Evolution: The Unfolding Narrative

[Evolution](/Evolution) is the grand, slow alteration of [heritable](/Heritable) characteristics in populations over generations. It's the engine behind new species and the silent architect of extinctions. [83](/Life#cite_note-83) [84](/Life#cite_note-84) Processes like [natural selection](/Natural_selection), [genetic drift](/Genetic_drift), and mutation continuously sculpt the tapestry of life, altering the frequency of traits within populations. [85](/Life#cite_note-85) This relentless process has generated the astounding [biodiversity](/Biodiversity) we observe across all levels of [biological organisation](/Biological_organisation). [86](/Life#cite_note-86) [87](/Life#cite_note-87)

#### Fossils: Whispers from the Past

[Fossils](/Fossils) are the preserved remnants of ancient life, offering glimpses into epochs long gone. The fossil record, encompassing all discovered and undiscovered fossils, is organized by [strata](/Strata) in [sedimentary rock](/Sedimentary_rock). A fossil is defined as any preserved specimen older than 10,000 years, spanning from the [Holocene](/Holocene) Epoch back to the [Archaean](/Archean) Eon, over 3.4 [billion](/1000000000_(number)) years ago. [89](/Life#cite_note-89) [90](/Life#cite_note-90)

#### Extinction: The Necessary End

[Extinction](/Extinction) is the final act for a [species](/Species), the moment the last individual dies. [91](/Life#cite_note-91) Given the vastness of species' ranges, pinpointing this exact moment is often an retrospective exercise. Species vanish when they can no longer adapt to changing [habitats](/Habitat) or compete with dominant rivals. A staggering 99% of all species that have ever existed are now extinct. [92](/Life#cite_note-92) [93](/Life#cite_note-93) [94](/Life#cite_note-94) [95](/Life#cite_note-95) Yet, these [mass extinctions](/Mass_extinction) have also paved the way for new evolutionary radiations. [96](/Life#cite_note-96)

### Environmental Conditions: The Stage for Life

The incredible diversity of life on Earth is a product of intricate interplay between genetic potential, metabolic capabilities, [environmental](/Environment_(biophysical)) pressures, and [symbiosis](/Symbiosis). [97](/Life#cite_note-97) [98](/Life#cite_note-98) [99](/Life#cite_note-99) [100](/Life#cite_note-100) For most of Earth's history, [microorganisms](/Microorganism) have been the dominant force, their metabolism and evolution shaping the planet's physical and chemical environment over [geologic time scales](/Geologic_time_scale). The release of [oxygen](/Oxygen) by [cyanobacteria](/Cyanobacteria) through [photosynthesis](/Photosynthesis) is a prime example, fundamentally altering the atmosphere and posing new evolutionary challenges that ultimately led to the emergence of complex life. [97](/Life#cite_note-97) This dynamic relationship between life and its environment is a defining characteristic of living systems.

#### Biosphere: Earth's Living Envelope

The [biosphere](/Biosphere) encompasses all of Earth's ecosystems, forming a largely self-regulating, closed system (apart from external energy inputs). [102](/Life#cite_note-102) Life, in its myriad forms, thrives in virtually every corner of this sphere, from the deepest oceans to the upper atmosphere, and even within solid rock. [103](/Life#cite_note-103) [104](/Life#cite_note-104) [105](/Life#cite_note-105) Spores of [Aspergillus niger](/Aspergillus_niger), for instance, have been found at altitudes of up to 77 km. [106](/Life#cite_note-106) Life has demonstrated an astonishing ability to survive in the vacuum of space under controlled conditions. [107](/Life#cite_note-107) [108](/Life#cite_note-108) Organisms persist in the extreme pressures of the [Mariana Trench](/Mariana_Trench), [109](/Life#cite_note-109) deep within the seafloor, and even beneath Antarctic ice. [113](/Life#cite_note-113) [114](/Life#cite_note-114) In the [Nankai Trough](/Nankai_Trough), [unicellular](/Unicellular) life has been found thriving in sediments at 120°C, 1.2 km below the seafloor. [115](/Life#cite_note-115) As one researcher noted, "You can find [microbes](/Microbe) everywhere—they're extremely adaptable to conditions, and survive wherever they are." [110](/Life#cite_note-110)

#### Range of Tolerance: Surviving the Extremes

The inert components of an ecosystem—energy, water, heat, [atmosphere](/Earth%27s_atmosphere), [nutrients](/Nutrient), and protection from [ultraviolet](/Ultraviolet) [solar radiation](/Ozone_layer)—provide the essential conditions for life. [116](/Life#cite_note-116) Within these ecosystems, organisms must navigate a fluctuating range of conditions, known as their "range of tolerance." Outside this range lie zones of physiological stress, where survival is precarious, and zones of intolerance, where life is impossible. Organisms with a broad range of tolerance are, unsurprisingly, more widely distributed. [117](/Life#cite_note-117)

#### Extremophiles: Life's Tenacious Survivors

Some microorganisms have evolved to defy the odds, thriving in conditions that would annihilate most life: extreme cold ([psychrophiles](/Psychrophile)), complete dehydration ([xerophiles](/Xerophile)), starvation ([oligotrophs](/Oligotroph)), and intense [radiation](/Radioresistance). [97](/Life#cite_note-97) [118](/Life#cite_note-118) These [extremophiles](/Extremophile) are masters of exploiting unusual energy sources. The study of their [morphology](/Morphology_(biology)) and metabolic diversity in [extreme environments](/Extreme_environment) is an ongoing frontier. [119](/Life#cite_note-119)

### Classification: Trying to Bring Order to Chaos

#### Antiquity: Aristotle's Framework

The earliest attempts at classifying life are attributed to [Aristotle](/Aristotle) (384–322 BC). He broadly divided organisms into [plants](/Plant) and [animals](/Animal), distinguishing them by their ability to move. His classification of animals, based on the presence of blood (akin to [vertebrates](/Vertebrate) and [invertebrates](/Invertebrate)), and his categorization of blooded animals (viviparous quadrupeds, oviparous quadrupeds, birds, fishes, and whales) and bloodless animals (cephalopods, crustaceans, insects, shelled animals, and "zoophytes"), remained influential for over a thousand years. [120](/Life#cite_note-120)

#### The Linnaean System: A Structured Approach

In the late 1740s, [Carl Linnaeus](/Carl_Linnaeus) introduced his groundbreaking system of [binomial nomenclature](/Binomial_nomenclature), revolutionizing how species were classified. He aimed for clarity and conciseness, refining existing terminology and introducing new descriptive terms. [121](/Life#cite_note-121)

Initially, [fungi](/Fungus) were grouped with [plants](/Plant). [Herbert Copeland](/Herbert_Copeland_(biologist)) later placed them within [Protoctista](/Protoctista), acknowledging their unique status. [122](/Life#cite_note-122) [Robert Whittaker](/Robert_Whittaker_(ecologist)) eventually established a dedicated [kingdom](/Kingdom_(biology)) for fungi in his [five-kingdom system](/Five-kingdom_system). [Evolutionary history](/Evolutionary_history) now shows fungi are more closely related to animals than plants. [123](/Life#cite_note-123)

The advent of [microscopy](/Microscopy) revealed a hidden world of microorganisms, leading to the fields of [cell biology](/Cell_biology) and [microbiology](/Microbiology). [Ernst Haeckel](/Ernst_Haeckel) proposed the kingdom [Protista](/Protista) to house these novel organisms. Later, [prokaryotes](/Prokaryote) were separated into the kingdom [Monera](/Monera), which was eventually split into [Bacteria](/Bacteria) and [Archaea](/Archaea), leading to the [six-kingdom system](/Six-kingdom_system) and ultimately the current [three-domain system](/Three-domain_system) based on evolutionary relationships. [124](/Life#cite_note-124)

However, the classification of eukaryotes, particularly protists, remains a contentious area. [125](/Life#cite_note-125)

The discovery of [viruses](/Virus), with their non-cellular nature, added another layer of complexity. Their status as "alive" is debated, as they lack many characteristics of life. [126](/Life#cite_note-126)

