### Composition: The Building Blocks

#### Chemical Elements: The Universal Ingredients

All life relies on a core set of [chemical elements](/Chemical_element) for its existence: [carbon](/Carbon), [hydrogen](/Hydrogen), [nitrogen](/Nitrogen), [oxygen](/Oxygen), [phosphorus](/Phosphorus), and [sulfur](/Sulfur). [138](/Life#cite_note-138) These elements form the backbone of [nucleic acids](/Nucleic_acid), proteins, and [lipids](/Lipid), the essential macromolecules of life. Carbon's ability to form stable [covalent bonds](/Covalent_bond) allows for the immense structural diversity seen in [organic chemistry](/Organic_chemistry). [139](/Life#cite_note-139) While hypothetical alternative biochemistries have been proposed, these six elements form the foundation of all known life. [140](/Life#cite_note-140) [141](/Life#cite_note-141)

#### DNA: The Blueprint

Deoxyribonucleic acid, or [DNA](/DNA), is the molecule that carries the [genetic](/Genetics) instructions for the development, functioning, and [reproduction](/Reproduction) of all known living [organisms](/Organism). [142](/Life#cite_note-142) It's a double helix structure, composed of two [polynucleotide](/Polynucleotide) strands. Each strand consists of [nucleotides](/Nucleotide), made of a [nucleobase](/Nucleobase) (A, T, C, or G), a [sugar](/Monosaccharide) called [deoxyribose](/Deoxyribose), and a [phosphate group](/Phosphate_group). The pairing of bases (A with T, C with G) through [hydrogen bonds](/Hydrogen_bond) is crucial for DNA's ability to store and replicate information. [143](/Life#cite_note-143) DNA is organized into [chromosomes](/Chromosome) within the [cell nucleus](/Cell_nucleus) in eukaryotes. [144](/Life#cite_note-144)

#### Cells: The Fundamental Units

[Cells](/Cell_(biology)) are the basic structural and functional units of all life, arising from pre-existing cells through [division](/Cell_division). [145](/Life#cite_note-145) [146](/Life#cite_note-146) This principle, [cell theory](/Cell_theory), revolutionized biology in the 19th century. [147](/Life#cite_note-147) The activities of an organism are the sum of its cellular activities, fueled by [energy flow](/Cellular_respiration). Cells contain the hereditary information passed down through generations. [148](/Life#cite_note-148)

There are two primary cell types:
*   **[Prokaryotes](/Prokaryote):** Simpler cells lacking a nucleus and membrane-bound [organelles](/Organelle). [Bacteria](/Bacteria) and [Archaea](/Archaea) belong to this group.
*   **[Eukaryotes](/Eukaryote):** More complex cells with a distinct nucleus and specialized organelles like [mitochondria](/Mitochondria) and [chloroplasts](/Chloroplasts). All complex multicellular organisms—animals, [plants](/Plant), and [fungi](/Fungus)—are eukaryotes, alongside diverse [protist](/Protist) microorganisms. [149](/Life#cite_note-149) The prevailing theory suggests eukaryotes evolved from prokaryotes through [endosymbiosis](/Endosymbiosis). [150](/Life#cite_note-150)

Cellular processes, from synthesis to signaling, are driven by [proteins](/Protein), often assembled through [protein biosynthesis](/Protein_biosynthesis) guided by [gene expression](/Gene_expression). [151](/Life#cite_note-151) In eukaryotes, the [Golgi apparatus](/Golgi_apparatus) plays a key role in protein processing and transport. [152](/Life#cite_note-152)

Cells reproduce through [cell division](/Cell_division). Prokaryotes divide by [fission](/Fission_(biology)), while eukaryotes undergo [mitosis](/Mitosis). For many species, [sexual reproduction](/Sexual_reproduction), involving [meiosis](/Meiosis), has been a critical evolutionary innovation. [154](/Life#cite_note-154) [155](/Life#cite_note-155)

#### Multicellular Structure: Cooperation and Specialization

The evolution of [multicellular organisms](/Multicellular_organism) likely began with colonies of identical cells. Over time, these cells developed specialized roles, leading to true multicellularity where individual cells rely on the collective for survival. This specialization allows for greater efficiency and complexity. [156](/Life#cite_note-156) A minor genetic shift in the [enzyme](/Enzyme) [GK-PID](/GK-PID) approximately 800 million years ago may have been a crucial step in this transition. [157](/Life#cite_note-157)

Cells communicate through [cell signaling](/Cell_signaling) to coordinate activities. This communication can be direct (juxtacrine signaling) or indirect via signaling molecules. In complex organisms, dedicated [nervous systems](/Nervous_system) provide rapid coordination. [158](/Life#cite_note-158)

### Life in the Universe: Are We Alone?

While life is only confirmed on Earth, the possibility of [extraterrestrial life](/Extraterrestrial_life) is widely considered plausible, even probable. [159](/Life#cite_note-159) [160](/Life#cite_note-160) The search extends to planets and moons within our [Solar System](/Solar_System] and beyond, investigating potential past or present habitats. [162](/Life#cite_note-162) [163](/Life#cite_note-163) Projects like [SETI](/SETI) actively listen for signals from alien civilizations.

The resilience of life on Earth, particularly [extremophiles](/Extremophile), provides valuable insights into the potential conditions for life elsewhere. [118](/Life#cite_note-118) For example, [lichen](/Lichen) has shown remarkable survival capabilities in simulated Martian environments. [165](/Life#cite_note-165) [166](/Life#cite_note-166)

Beyond our solar system, the [habitable zone](/Habitable_zone) around a star defines the region where Earth-like conditions might exist. Factors like stellar mass and activity influence this zone's size and stability. [167](/Life#cite_note-167) A star's location within a galaxy, balancing the availability of heavy elements for planet formation with a low rate of destructive [supernova](/Supernova) events, may also play a role in the likelihood of complex life. [168](/Life#cite_note-168) The [Drake equation](/Drake_equation) attempts to quantify these probabilities, though with considerable uncertainty. [169](/Life#cite_note-169) A "Confidence of Life Detection" (CoLD) scale has been proposed for reporting such discoveries. [170](/Life#cite_note-170) [171](/Life#cite_note-171)

#### Artificial Life and Synthetic Biology: Mimicking and Creating

[Artificial life](/Artificial_life) explores the simulation of life's aspects through computation and [robotics](/Robotics). [172](/Life#cite_note-172) [Synthetic biology](/Synthetic_biology), a burgeoning field, merges science and [biological engineering](/Biological_engineering) to design and construct novel biological systems with functions not found in nature. Its aims are broad, encompassing information processing, chemical manipulation, material fabrication, energy production, and enhancing human health and the environment. [173](/Life#cite_note-173)

